column168: Driver recognized material leaking from front of trailer upon turning onto entrance ramp.  Pulled over to investigate and discovered that an IBC of 50% sodium hydroxide solution was leaking.  The IBC was found to have a 10" vertical crack approximately 8" above the base of a corner radius.  Cause of the package failure is undetermined.  Driver acted to contain the material leaking from the trailer with plastic sheeting and absorbant materials.  Driver then acted to minimize the amount leaking from the IBC by applying a patch and strap over the crack.  Local Sherrif Deputy, MI State Police (DOT), and Niles Township FD HazMat unit were on scene to control situation.  Spill contactor was called to the scene by the shipper.  Total quantity of HM lost was 20 gallons.  Remaining material in IBC was transferred to appropriate containers (UN 1H1 drums), free liquids in trailer absorbed and transferred to 1H2 drum, contained liquid below trailer transferred to 1H1 drum, and impacted soil removed to 1H2 drum.  Containers were secured for transport and returned to the shippers location.  Contents of trailer were removed, and trailer cleaned by contractor.  Remaining product to be used internally.  Wastes to be disposed of appropriately.
column169: Cause of package failure is unknown at this time.  Given the age of the IBC, degradation is suspected.  Further investigation to be conducted.  Based upon conclusions, appropriate actions to be taken.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While at the rail yard, free product was discovered leaking from the trailer.  H.M.H.T.T.C. Response, Inc. of Carlisle, Pennsylvania was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  H.M.H.T.T.C. Response, Inc. investigated the trailer and discovered three leaking five-gallon plastic pails at the half mark of the trailer.  Approximately five gallons of free product were released.  The damage to the pails was due to improper loading.  The freight was overstacked and not properly braced.  H.M.H.T.T.C. Response, Inc. performed the cleanup using absorbents.  The cleanup materials were placed into two, five-gallon recovery drums.  The three damaged pails were placed into a recovery drum and will be forwarded with the remainder of the shipment.  H.M.H.T.T.C. Response, Inc. will coordinate disposal of the waste.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The Material Safety Data Sheet was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and may have been the cause of a shipper error, no actions have been taken to prevent future incidents.

column168: 2 20-liter drums were declared on the shipping paper as 1 wooden box containing 2 drums of oil. The drums were not actually in a box, they were placed in between two pallets and the pallets were banded together. The pallets apparently rubbed against the drums causing them to crack and leak the majority of the liquid. When the spill was found at the Carlisle, PA terminal, the dock person noticed Marine Pollutant stickers on the containers. After extensive conversation with the shipper who totally denied any wrong doing and denied the material was hazmat, I finally received an MSDS the next day that confirmed the material to be Env Haz Sub Liquid NOS but no technical name was provided.
column169: Correct declaration of the dangerous good and correct packaging would have prevented this spill. The plastic containers should not have been banded in between two pallets with no layer of protection immediately between the drums and skids.

column168: The hazardous materials transporter Triad Transport, Inc. delivered a shipment of old transformers to the Onyx Environmental Services 10-day transfer facility located in Baytown, Texas on October 7, 2005 at 0930.  The transformers were approximately 55 to 85 gallons in size.  As this shipment of Transformers was being unloaded from one trailer to be placed in another trailer for delivery to the final destination, employees discovered that three of the transformers were leaking.  The leak appeared to be around some connections or attachments on the external shell of the three  transformers.  Oil absorbent was placed around the transformers and all along the floor of the trailer.  It was estimated that a total of one gallon had spilled into the van trailer.  The shipment was off-loaded onto plastic sheeting.  The liquid contents of the leaking transformers were transferred to metal drums to prevent any further spillage.  All the contents, new containers, and the transformers were then loaded onto a van trailer for shipment to the final destination.
column169: Notification has been made to the transporter who first picked up the shipment of transformers about proper handling of this type of material.  Better procedures must be in place for handling transformers to prevent damage.

column168: Shipment originated in London destined to Baltimore, Maryland via Newark, New Jersey.  Shipment discoved leaking at final destination during unloading phase.  The amount of spill was 6 inches by 6 inches, approximated at less than 0.5 liters.    Spill contained in cargo hold and cleaned by company mechanics.  Fire brigade contacted for inspection - results of Fire brigade report pending.  Request for copy of report made and awaiting delivery.    1 of 14 boxes leaked - outer package not opened by airline personnel. Leakaging package contained in plastic bin to prevent further leakage.    Company Mechanic verified spillage contained to surface of cargo hold.    Leakage package thought to be inadequate inner receptacle leaked with presure differential.  Carrier unable to prove/disprove this fact.  Carrier did not open packages to inspect due to potentail harm to health.  Carrier recommends Specification packaging be utilized for future shipments.      Release was condined to one package with maximum release of then (10) liters.  Spill reported to local Fire department for remediation.  Repinse report available upon request.
column169: Recommendation to shipper for specifaction packaging and greater performance inner packaging.    Carrier is investigating past shipments from shipper in an effort to decide if choice of packaging (Limited Quantity) is cause of failures.  Carrier plans to require Specification packaging by shipper for future shipments.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While traveling on Interstate 71, Northbound at mile-marker 9.4 in Louisville, Kentucky free product was discovered leaking from the Inca, Inc. cargo tank.  The Louisville Fire Department, Kentucky Highway Department, Jefferson County Emergency Management Agency, Kentucky Natural Resources and Environmental Protection Cabinet and the United States Department of Transportation responded to the scene.  The Kentucky Highway Department placed down sand to contain and absorb the free product.  All northbound lanes of Interstate 71 were shut down for approximately 3 hours.  Evergreen Environmental of Crestwood, Kentucky was contacted to perform the cleanup.  Evergreen Environmental placed additional absorbent materials and boom on the affected asphalt and a containment pool under the leaking cargo tank to contain the free product and prevent further migration.  Further investigation determined that approximately, one hundred and sixty-three gallons of free product was released.  Apparently, the release was due to structural damage of the cargo tank.  The exact cause of release is under investigation.  Evergreen Environmental transferred the contents of the leaking cargo tank into another cargo tank provided by Inca, Inc.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The MSDS was requested and received.  All federal, state and local regulatory agencies were notified.
column169: Since the release was accidental and the cause of the release is under investigation, plans do not currently exist to prevent recurrence.

column168: The tractor trailer had exited from interstate 75 south to connector 3 in Dalton Georgia.    The vehicle proceeded from a stop at a traffic light turning left or east onto the overpass of connector 3. Upon completing the turn and moving at approximately 5 mph the driver noticed the left side tires of the trailer were off of the roadway and the trailer was leaning to the right. Once the tractor and trailer were stright there was no leverage of the tractor holding the trailer upright and both units turned over on the right side onto the roadway.    The trailer was loaded with nine IBCs each filled with 296 gallons of Sodium Hydroxide 50% Solution. Due to the force of the IBCs stiking the wall of the trailer upon contact with the roadway, one two inch closure installed in a larger seven inch closure was ejected from one container by the force of the liquid impacting the head of the IBC.    Since the IBC was on its side approximately one half of the content or 138 gallons was released into the trailer subsequently escaping onto the roadway and a portion of the liquid came in contact with soil adjacent to the area. This release occured over a 15 minute period.    The local fire department responded initially and contacted a local environmental response contractor to secure the scene and perform cleanup operations. These cleanup activities concluded the following day at approximately 7:30 am.    The Sodium Hydroxide spilled from the container was collected, either in liquid form and transferred to suitable containers or solidified using absorbent and placed in a collection container along with the soil in contact with the material for disosal.
column169: Personnel reviewed loading, blocking and bracing procedures and received training both prior to and after the incident as required by the Hazmat Employee Training requirements. Drivers received training for the mandatory requirement of inspecting loads prior to departure and enroute for conditions that may allow containers to move or shift during transportation.

column42: ENGINES INTERNAL COMBUSTION, OR ENGINES, FUEL CELL, FLAMMABLE LIQUID POWERED
column168: A crate was tendered as a non-hazardous shipment.  It was originally scheduled to move to ANC on our freighter.  Shipper wanted it to leave earlier on a passenger flight.  The crate was too large to fit throught the belly door of our passenger aircraft.  The shippers representative came out to our facility to see if they could shorten the crate.  When it was opened we discovered that the contents were an internal combustion engine.  The engine was not new and had a gas tank attached.  The tank was empty but contained some fuel residue.  There were no markings or labeling to indicate there was an engine inside.    We immediately set the shipment aside and placed a hold on it.  We contacted the local FAA Haz-Mat office.  The examined and photographed the crate and started an investigation.  They released the shipment back to us and the shipper terminated it and picked it up later that afternoon.
column169: Our company does an excellent job of using trigger terms to determine if there could be concealed haz-mat.  In this case there was nothing to indicate further probing should be done.  We will continue to train for trigger terms and use our mandated securit inspections to aid us with discovering undeclared dangerous goods.

column168: While unloading inbound trailer, shipment was discovered to have one 5 gallon pail of paint leaking.  Although it is unclear as to exact cause, it would appear that other freight that was loaded next to the paint struck the pail, denting the side of the pail and causing a small crack.  Approximately one pint of contents was released.  Spill was contained and cleaned up at unloading facility.  Damaged pail was held in haz mat bay for disposal via environmental contractor.
column169: Notice was sent to loading terminal to review loading practices and use of dunnage.  A small amount of cardboard dunnage along the side of the pails would have been sufficient to prevent this type of damage.  Shipment was packaged adequately for transport as received from shipper.

column168: While on the dock one drum was forked.  The spilled material was cleaned up with a clay absorbent and packed into a bag.  The damaged drum was overpacked into a salvage container and placed in OS & D.

column168: Supervisor statement: 20 gallons crude oil released. States to much back pressure on unloading line. Drivers were having problems with pressure at the header since tanks were relocated. Customer has pressure set at 30 lbs with one truck unloading. 2nd truck increases the pressure. Fitting blew off hose during this event (2 trucks were unloading). All spilled product was contained on caliche pad. Koch handled containment and clean up of spill.    ***UPDATE*** Rec'd a clean up invoice from Miller Environmental in the amount stated. Costs updated 01/04/2006
column169: Discussion with Koch and Mission personnel to have pressure reduced.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While moving freight at the BAX Global facility, one, one hundred and eighty-five liter metal drum was punctured by a forklift.  Approximately, ten gallons of free product were released.  H.M.H.T.T.C. of Wilmington, DE was contacted to perform the cleanup.  H.M.H.T.T.C. performed the cleanup using absorbent pads.  The cleanup materials were placed into an overpack drum which will be returned to the shipper.  The remainder of the shipment will be forwarded to the consignee.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The MSDS was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental and the result of a puncture by a forklift, plans due not currently exist to prevent recurrence.

column168: The shipment was offered under a vessel sharing agreement to Hapag-Lloyd Container Line as non hazardous material by P & O Nedlloyd Lines, on behalf of their shipper, for transport on the Hapag-Lloyd container vessel Northern Fortune from Savannah, Georgia to Cagliari, Italy.     P & O Nedlloyd advised Hapag-Lloyd after vessel had sailed from Savannah that the shipment was not booked as hazardous materials, the shipping papers did not indicate the presence hazardous materials, and that the container was not placarded and/or marked.  P & O Nedlloyd subsequently provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers to Hapag-Lloyd.     Hapag-Lloyd advised the Master of the vessel of the undeclared hazardous materials onboard.

column168: Driver was hooked up with pump truck to railcar and transport trailer loading his trailer. Train stopped on main line to cut cars loose that were to be placed on our siding. The engineer blew his horn at our driver. The driver waved back at the engineer. They driver went back to watching his trailer as the train went on down the line to move into our siding. The driver assumed the crew was going to push the cars onto the sidng and return the next day to make the swap. At this location we are set up to have a swap on Monday, Wednesday and Friday. When the train stopped on the siding our driver started up the track toward a crew member walking down the track. They  waved at each other and our driver returned to watching his trailer as he was getting close to being loaded.The train crew member turned and started walking back up the track. As the driver was watching his trailer he noticed/heard the couplers tighten up on the cars. He looked down the track to see what was happening and saw a crew member standing over by the main line with his back turned toward our driver looking down toward the engine. As our driver began to move toward this crew member  waving and shouting trying to get his attention he looked back and saw the pump truck over turn. When the truck over turned the train crew member heard the noise turned around and saw what had happened and got the train stopped. This was the 3rd load of the day for this driver. He had placed his blue car connected sign at the beginning of his shift. He checked the sign when he returned for his second load and it was still in place. The driver did not check the 3rd time to see if the sign was in place. In interviewing both Rome drivers it has been the pratice that when the train crew came in and our truck was there a member of the crew  would walk down and ask if everything was ready for them to move the cars. On this day that did not take place. The only contact our driver had with the crew was when he waved at them from a distance.
column169: Each driver now has a blue stopped connected sign that they will place on the railcar before they start loading and will remove after they finish loading and take their sign with them. No sign will be left in place or hoses connected when a driver is not at the rail siding. Derailer will be installed that will be locked in place by each driver and unlocked when they leave.

column168: Forklift driver had loaded the totes onto a trailer, proceded to load a pallet of freight behind the totes. There was a metal object protruding from the opposite side of the pallet away from the forklift drivers view. The metal object punctured the plastic tote approximately 2 feet high in the middle of the tote. The puncture hole was 4 to 5 inches in width. The product released in approximately 5 minutes onto the ground behind the trailer. 4 yards of sand was dumped onto the spill to absorb the product and a certified hazmat recovery company was hired to clean up the spill and dispose of properly.
column169: We have implemented more and better training for our dock workers and forklift operators on the proper handling of hazmat shipments with special attention to totes and drums. As for recommendations for improvement of transporting and packaging I suggest that plastic totes should have better protection around them such as a complete metal case instead of a wire mesh with six inch gaps.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While at the BAX Global facility in Swanton, Ohio, a leak was discovered from a fiberboard carton.  The carton contained exhibit materials, which consisted of an assortment of items including flyers, binders, packing material, a steel carton, and two (2) plastic bottles of Sklar Disinfectant.  Upon opening the box, it was determined that the cap had come loose from one (1) 24 ounce plastic bottle of Sklar Disinfectant, and it had lost its contents inside the container.  The product had already dried upon discovery, and no free product remained.  The entire carton was placed into a poly bag, which was held in a recovery drum at the Toledo Hub, pending disposition from the shipper.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release occurred due to improper blocking and bracing of the product, BAX Global will continue to reinforce safety guidelines in relation to proper blocking and bracing of freight.

column168: IMPROPER LOADING TECHNIQUES BY DOCK ASSOCITES.
column169: COACH DOCK ASSOCIATES ON PROPER LOADING TECHNIQUES AND PROCEDURES SUCH AS BLOCKING,BRACING AND DUNNAGE.

column168: Driver of tanker was going southbound on RT 1098. On entering a curve he met a car on his side of the road. To avoid a collison with the car driver veered to his right. This occured where a culvert runs under the pavement of the road which is seriously eroded an approximate depth of 30 feet on either side. The trailer axles   dropped off the roadbed when the earth gave way.The tanker rolled over one and three quarter times and came to rest on its end within 15 feet of the pavement.The tractor, which had cleared the culvert, jack-knifed and came to rest on an embankment.Leakage came from the manway vents during the turning over process.Site  was secured by absorbent materials.Crude oil was removed by vacuum thru lower safety valves and loaded on another truck. The remainder was sucked from manhose and taken to secure site. No release visible during the uprighting of vehicle nor after. Absorbent pads were changed after a subsequent rain and site was monitored for several days.Earth disturbed was smoothed and strawed by KORC employees.
column169: Transporter was observing speed regulations and on his side of the highway when accident occurred. He used his best judgement to avoid the accident.

column168: Arrived at our destination terminal in a salvage drum, unknown what happened to the original drum. I checked with every terminal that touched the freight and we had no luck at finding out what happened to this drum.

column168: Container HDMU5935488 arrived California United Terminals on a NONHAZ booking on 10/13.  The container was not marked and no shipping papers were presented.  On 10/16, the container loaded the vessel (Hyundai Republic) bound for Hong Kong.  On 10/28, the freight forwarder informed Hyundai that there was undeclared hazmat in this running reefer, including 2 types of aerosols (UN1950) and a corrosive liquid (UN3267).  Vessel Master was notified, upon inspection, there was no incident or release.

column168: Driver had to move the cargo tank to another location within the customers facility. He closed the domelid, but did not secure it. column168: Bobtail driver saw the vehicle in front of him lock up his brakes and could not stop in time. The left side of bobtail struck the passenger side of truck in front of him. To avoid the accident our driver swerved to the right and ended up striking the guardrail and the side of vehicle ahead. No release of propane and no injury.    The flex connectors on the LPG piping were distorted and creased, requiring repairs.
column169: After each such accident a committee reviews the investigative facts to determine whether the driver followed company safety practices and whether disciplinary actions are appropriate.    Our employees receive recurrent training for defensive driving, proper backing techniques and how to prevent rollovers. Employees must pass a driver recertification test every three years. Remedial measures will be taken.

column168: Driver had completed transferring product from cargo tank to the customer storage tank.  He did not properly relieve the pressure in the line before disconnecting the hose from the customer's tank and some product sprayed out.  Driver was not wearing the proper PPE that we require and got product on his face and in his eyes.  The plant personnel immediately took water hose to clean him off and flushed his eyes.  Driver was taken by ambulance to air lift location so he could receive attention as quickly as possible to eliminate or reduce any eye damage. Driver was admitted to the hospital for one day as a precaution and then discharged.  He had one follow up visit to his doctor and then released back to work on 10/17.  Driver had been wearing his personal reading glasses, rain jacket, gloves, hard hat and work boots when the incident occured.
column169: Incident could have been prevented if driver wore the proper PPE that was prescribed for this product.  Along with our basic PPE requirements, this product required a chemical suit and goggles.  This information was sent via computer to the driver before he was dispatched on the load.  Also listed was the notation "may cause severe eye burns". Driver placed himself in extreme risk by deciding not to wear the proper PPE.  Driver received remedial training on the importance of wearing PPE and also procedures for disconnecting.

column168: Driver began to transfer product from cargo tank to customer storage tank and they discovered that the valve at the bottom of the customer tank was leaking.  About 1/2 gallon went into the containment area.  Driver shut down, customer fixed the leaky valve and rest of product was unloaded without further incident.  Spill was cleaned up with spill pads.
column169: Valve on consignee storage tank was leaking.  It was fixed to prevent leaking in the future.

column168: Driver started to transfer product from cargo tank to customer storage tank using product pump on our tractor.  Fluid started to leak from the pump.  Driver shut down.  product went on concrete and consignee wanted an environmental firm to clean it up.  We called in Garner Environmental Services who cleaned up the 1 gallon spill and stood by while we got another pump to the site to finish the offload.
column169: This was the first time the pump was used since being installed on the tractor.  Upon examining the pump after the incident, it was determined that the pump came from the factory with a plug missing.  It would have been hard for the driver to notice it because it isn't something the driver would typically check.  It was in an area hard to see.

column168: Driver transferring product from cargo tank to customer storage tank.  Driver was by trailer and plant employee by the storage tank watching the sight gauge.  The storage tank overflowed about 10 gal.  Still 475 gallons of product in trailer.  Customer believes their sight glass was in accurate.  Customer clean up spill according to regulations.
column169: Sight gauge needs to be checked out before any further deliveries to this tank.

column168: Shipmnet arrived on Delta 517 from Miami, FL. - No damage was noted at arrival. It was staged at our transport area for transfer to flight 355 to Boston, MA. at 1810. When our transfer agent returned to cart, the cylinder had collapsed and imploded. At 2200, the transfer driver brought the cylinder to our Domestic warehouse and it was immediately quarantined. It continued to slowly vent/leak Liquid Nitrogen from the pressure valve on top until empty. The FAA was notified of the incident. They came to our facility, photographed the shipment, and released the shipment. Subsequently the shipper was notified of the incident and was contacted for pick up. They made local arrangements for re-packaging and re-tender.
column169: Appears that some packaging errors were made. Unsure of the reliability of their packaging standard. Reccommend shipper uses appropriate packaging for future shipments.

column168: This was not a UN 3028 as reported; however, to complete the form an entry was required. This was a Dry Battery - Not Restricted.     TSA Baggage sceeners notified Delta at approximately 0930 on 10/21/2005 that a checked bag belonging to Mike Dixon traveling on flight 4011 was emitting smoke. they discovered a DeWalt 18V cordless drill battery inside a small duffle bag contained in a larger suitcase. The battery had apparently shorted when it contact metal screws contained in the same duffle bag. The battery was hot. Its connector terminals had melted, burning a hole throughthe duffle bag and singeing a pair of jeans packed in the larger bag. The hole and singe marks were approximately one inch in diameter. The battery pack was removed and the bag and jeans were photgraphed. The remainder of the contents were inspected and then dispatched to the aircraft. The customer was notified and stated the item was new and still under warranty. The battery was held for inspection. Local FAA was also notified.
column169: If this is a trend with DeWalt batteries, the manufacturer may need to be contacted for recall, or re-design.

column168: BNSF DISPATCHER REPORTED TRACK INDICATIONS ON CTC SIGNALED TERRITORY AFTER A BNSF TRAIN PASSED THROUGH IT. THE TRACK INDICATIONS STARTED BETWEEN THE MAIN TRACK SWITCHES AT BROWNING, MT. THIS TRAIN WAS STOPPED AND INSPECTED AT BISON, MT. ENTRAINED COVERED HOPPER PTLX 15262 (WHICH WAS ADDED TO THIS TRAIN AT SHELBY, MT) WAS FOUND LEAKING PRODUCT FROM ONE OF THE THREE BOTTOM OUTLETS. PTLX 15262 WAS SETOUT OF THE TRAIN AT THE INDUSTRY TRACK AT SUMMIT, MT. RESPONDING SIGNAL MAINTAINERS FOUND SMALL PILES OF PRODUCT SPILLAGE ALONG THE RIGHT-OF-WAY AT VARIOUS LOCATIONS IN THE 25 MILE SECTION OF MAIN TRACK BETWEEN BROWNING AND SUMMIT. SPILLED PRODUCT MIXING WITH RAIN APPARENTLY CONTRIBUTED TO THE SIGNAL SYSTEM PROBLEM. A CONTRACTOR WITH A VACUUM TRUCK VACUUMED ALL SPILLAGE ALONG THIS IMPACTED TRACK SEGMENT. BNSF MECHANICAL RESPONDERS FOUND PTLX 15262'S B-END BOTTOM HOPPER OUTLET GATE (DOOR) NOT LOCKED AND SLIGHTLY OPEN WITH A SMALL PILE OF PRODUCT UNDER THIS OPENING. THIS OUTLET WAS CLOSED BY THE RESPONDERS. RESPONDERS ALSO FOUND THE C (MIDDLE) BOTTOM HOPPER OUTLET GATE WITH THE CLOSING MECHANISM ASKEW, BUT NO PRODUCT APPARENTLY WAS LEAKING FROM THIS MIDDLE OUTLET. THE RESPONDERS PROPERLY REALLIGNED THIS CLOSING MECHANISM. THESE TWO OUTLETS WERE NOT LOCKED OR SEALED. SOME SEALS WERE VISIBLE AT THE OPPOSITE END FROM THE LOCKING DEVICE. REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED PRIOR TO 1100 HRS. MDT ON 10/01/05.
column169: ENSURE SHIPPER'S PRE-TRIP INSPECTION PROCESS IS FULLY IMPLEMENTED AND VALIDATED AS IT PERTAINS TO THE MECHANICAL FITNESS AND SECUREMENT OF ALL CLOSURES, VALVES AND FITTINGS.

column168: When driver went to pick up preloaded cargo tank at shipper, he noticed <1 gallon of product on ground under the external valve.  They were able to tighten the nut on the shaft on the external valve to stop the drip.  They drained the product in the line which indicated the internal valve was not completely holding.  They reseated the internal valve but product still dripped out.  Trailer was in a containment area.  The product was transferred to a different trailer so it could be checked out.
column169: Trailer was checked out by a contracted maintenance facilty and they could find nothing wrong.  Trailer has been under several loads since then with no problem.  Not sure why product dripped before unless there was something in the trailer that prevented the internal from fully closing.

column168: Royster-Clark assoicate, Doug Olson, was driving a tractor hitched to a toolbar and ammonia wagon to the customer's field.  The tongue broke on the nurse wagon hitch and the wagon pushed the toolbar into the ditch.  While correcting for the toolbar into the ditch, the nurse wagon overturned and the front unload valve on the ammonia wagon broke and released anhydrous ammonia.  Mr. Olson called 911 and the JoDaviess Co. sheriff, HazMat Team, the Stockton Fire Dept. responded.  The Royster-Clark HazMat team from East Dubuque, IA, also responded.  The Royster-Clark HazMat team cut off the rollbar that was protecting the valves so that they could break off the liquid valve and plug the opening with a pipe and a valve.  Ammonia was released from the valve for approximately 20 minutes.  The tank was uprighted and the tongue was replaced.  The tank was then pulled back to the Lanark, IL, location so that it could be weighed and pumped-off.
column169: All anhydrous ammonia nurse wagons with tongues of that same design will be taken to a machine shop to be redesigned prior to the 2006 season.

column168: FILE 05-96 FAA SHIPPER-COMPASS MARKETING AWB#- FFM 26723040746 GSP  ON 10/07/2005 AT 0156, A LEAKING SHIPMENT WAS REPORTED IN "C" BUILDING OF OUR MAIN SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. SPILL TECHNICIAN LOREN LORENZO DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL, HE FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE. HE REMOVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN HIS INVESTIGATION. UPON THIS INVESTIGATION, HE FOUND THIS PACKAGE TO CONTAIN 6 X 18 OUNCE METAL AEROSOL CANS MARKED CONTENTS UNDER PRESSURE. THIS PRODUCT DID NOT LEAK, BUT WAS NOT DECLARED AS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. THE LEAKING ITEM WAS NOT REGULATED. THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED INTO WILMINGTON VIA FLIGHT #197. THIS INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE GREAT LAKES REGION FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION.  THIS SHIPMENT DID NOT HAVE MARKINGS/LABELS OR A SHIPPERS DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING IT TO INDICATE THAT THIS WAS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 0220.  THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZMAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.

The Industrial Chemicals' driver pulled into the John N John, Inc. facility. After checking in, the driver removed the securement straps (2) from the sodium hydroxide IBC. John N John's forklift operator unloaded the sodium hydroxide IBC and placed it on the ground. the operator retrieved and loaded empty IBC's onto the trailer. A manager signed the driver's bill of lading and the driver began securing the empty IBC's. The forklift operator picked up the sodium hydroxide IBC and began moving it across the yard to its point of use. As he crossed the yard, the sodium hydroxide IBC slid off the forks, fell to the ground and ruptured causing the sodium hydroxide to spill from the tank. At this point John N John personnel advised the driver that they would handle containment, clean-up and disposal of the spilled material. The driver finished securing the empty IBC's and departed the John N John facility as directed.
column169: Additional training for John N John forklift operators.

column168: The driver had arrived to load his second load and after loading the second load the driver failed to close his dome lid and departed the loading station at the customers location. The Fire Department was notified and closed the roadway in the east bound lanes. ATC Environmental was contacted and they dispatched a clean-up crew to the scene. Soda ash and lime was used to neutralize the spilled product. The neutralized product was swept up off the raodway and loaded into a truck and taken to Clark Environmental for disposal by ACT Environmental. The road was re-opened to 1 lane after 3 hours and at 1:30 PM the road was open completely.
column169: CTL has installed a brake inter-lock system device to the dome lid to test this type of application and will begin an installation program if this application holds up in this type of service. This type of system will not allow the trailer brakes to be released if the dome lid opening is not properly secured.

Driver had finished offloading from rail car and was putting away hoses when he noticed a minute liquid leak from the “A” side liquid valve on the rail car. column168: AT 1217 ON 10/5/05, AN EMPLOYEE OF CSX WAS IN THE PROCESS OF SWITCHING CARS AT BARR YARD, IN RIVERDALE, IL. HAYWOOD, CAUSING 1ST DEGREE BURNS TO HIS HEAD AND FACE.  EMPLOYEE HAYWOOD WAS TRANSPORTED TO INGELL'S HOSPITAL, WHERE HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED.  MR. column168: The driver returned to the facility at approximately 9:30 PM on October 24, 2005, with 2 drums of resin product. These drums were scheduled to be delivered earlier in the day to our customer in Horsham, PA.  However, due to a delay, the driver was not able to make delivery and brought the two drums back to our facility at 9525-D Berger Road in Columbia, MD.    Upon return, our personnel noticed that one of the two drums had been punctured in the lower half.  A small amount of the material leaked onto the floor of the van trailer.  Most of the material leaked onto our warehouse floor.  Two to three gallons of material were released.  No material was released onto the environment.  Absorbent material was applied to the spilled material, which was picked up and properly disposed of.
column169: The driver is no longer working on behalf of our company.      Our company continues to emphasize proper load securement in our safety and regulatory training and in daily work practices.

column168: Driver said he pretripped trailer before he took it to load at shipper.  Shipper loaded the trailer from bottom with dome open.  Driver said he wasn't sure if they allowed him on trailer at that plant so he was going to go down to a truck stop to make sure everything was secure after loading. He wasn't allowed to stop outside of shipper gate.  About 5 miles from shipper, he stopped at a stop light and noticed product coming down side of trailer.  He went across intersection, put down triangles and flagged someone down to call the fire dept.  He had spill cleaned up with spill pads by time the fire dept got there.  They just said good job and left. Driver said the front washout cap was missing.  Some product dripped off trailer onto the asphalt shoulder and pretty much evaporated.  I called the VA Dept of Enviromental Quality to report it to them.  Someone in the office took a little info but said someone else would get back to me if they felt it was necessary. No one called back.
column169: Driver needs to make sure the cargo tank is secured before leaving the shipper.  He never asked if he could go on the trailer or even asked if loader secured it.  If he is not allowed on trailer and he is not sure that it is secure, he needs to get his safety department involved before he gets out on the roadway.

column168: Driver had finished transferring product from the cargo tank to customer storage tank.  He was disconnecting the transfer hose from the storage tank and spilled about 2 gallons of product that was still left in the fill line of the storage tank.  Driver and plant personnel used spill absorbant to clean up the spilled product on the concrete and plant properly disposed of it.
column169: Not sure if customer fill line had a shut off valve or not but that would have prevented product from remaining in the line if the line was properly cleared before disconnecting.

column168: Product was transferred from our cargo tank to customer storage tank.  Driver had filled tank to 90% and line was still full of product.  They were going to put hose into a tote to clear line.  Unloader was by tote and driver by trailer. Driver couldn't see unloader or tote so driver yelled that he was going to slowly open the line.  Unloader yelled ok.  When driver opened the valve, the unloader yelled stop.  The hose came out of the tote and sprayed side of building.  They hosed it down to their containment system.  No product got on anyone.
column169: Driver was reminded of procedures to blowing a line clear with low pressure.  Also it is not the best practice to blow lines into a tote.  Better communication between driver and plant operator might also have prevented spill.

column168: Driver had transferred 100 gallons of product from our cargo tank to the consignee's storage tank when the fill line for the storage tank started to leak. Driver shut down and delivered the rest of the product to a different storage tank.  Plant personnel were going to clean up the 1 gallon spill that went in a concrete containment area.
column169: Consignee equipment was at fault.  Fill line needs to be fixed before next delivery.

column168: The driver was in the process of off-loading the product at the customer facility while in the process the off-loading hose started to get a bubble on the off-loading hose approx. 8 inches from the male end of the hose. The driver immediately shut down the off-loading process. Approx. 1 gallon of product was released. The product was contained in the customer off-loading area on an impervious surface. The driver replaced the hose and finished unloading without further incident. The hose was in proper test date and had been tested in September of 2005.

BNSF MECHANICAL CARMAN REPORTED UCLX 16326 IN RAILYARD LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET AREA.  UCLX 16326 WAS ISOLATED IN THE RAILYARD.  CONTRACT AND SHIPPER RESPONDERS FOUND THE LEAK APPEARED TO BE ORIGINATING FROM THE BOTTOM OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE'S MOUNTING FLANGE.  FLANGE BOLTS WERE RETIGHTENED SLOWING THE LEAK RATE TO APPROXIMATELY ONE DRIP EVERY THREE SECONDS.  REMAINING PRODUCT IN UCLX 16326 WAS TRANSFERRED INTO ANOTHER SUITABLE TANK CAR, UCLX 16133, WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT ON 10/14.  UCLX 16326 WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR INVESTIGATION INTO THE FLANGE OR FLANGE GASKET FAILURE.  UCLX 16133 WAS ALSO RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR CONTAMINATION SAMPLING.  PRODUCT SPILLAGE EVIDENT IN THE RAILYARD WAS NEUTRALIZED.  LATER, SHIPPER REPORTED FINDING A FLAW (ROUGH METAL SURFACE) ON THE FLANGE GASKET SEATING AREA NEAR A FLANGE BOLT HOLE THAT LIKELY CONTRIBUTED TO THE LEAK.

column168: BN 974358 ON STORAGE TANK AWAITING UNLOADING WAS OBSERVED DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET T-CONFIGURATED UNLOADING PIPES.  A RECEPTACLE WAS PLACED UNDER THE DRIP AREA TO CATCH PRODUCT.  BNSF MECHANICAL RESPONDERS TIGHTENED THE BOLTED CONNECTION OF THE PIPING AT THE LEAK AREA, STOPPING THE RELEASE BY 1030 HRS. MDT, 10/08/05.  IT APPEARED THAT THE GASKET AT THE BOLTED PIPE CONNECTION JUST BEFORE THE T-JUNCTION WAS DRIED AND CRACKED; AND ALLOWED PRODUCT IN THE PIPING TO ESCAPE.  REMAINING PRODUCT IN BN 974358 WAS TRANSFERRED INTO ANOTHER SUITABLE TANK CAR ON 10/08/05 WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  AFTERWARDS BN 974358 WAS DIRECTED TO A REPAIR SHOP FOR REPAIRS TO THE BOTTOM OUTLET T-PIPING.

column168: DRIVER WAS TO UNLOAD ONE COMPARTMENT OF GASOLINE AT DOLLAR BAY GAS STATION AND THE THREE REMAINING COMPARTMENTS AT CALUMET. WHEN DRIVER ARRIVED AT DOLLAR BAY, HE WAS TOLD TO UNLOAD 3350 GALLON COMPARTMENT THERE. DRIVER HOOKED UP HOSE FROM OUR TRAILER TO UNDERGROUND TANK AND STARTED GAS FLOWING. HE MONITORED FLOW FOR 5 MINUTES AND SEEING ALL OK AND NO LEAKS, HE WENT TO BACK OF OUR TRAILER TO CHECK TIRES AND LIGHTS. HE THEN WENT TO OTHER SIDE OF THE TRAILER TO CHECK TIRES AND LIGHTS AND WALKED TO FRONT. AS HE CAME AROUND FRONT OF TRACTOR HE SAW GAS STATION'S TANK OVERFLOWING. HE RUSHED TO TRAILER VALVES AND SHUT THEM OFF. OUR DRIVER TOLD STATION ATTENDANT TO CALL CONSIGNEE AT CALUMET AND REPORT SPILL. DRIVER THEN TOOK OUR SPILL KIT FROM TRUCK AND PLACED ABSORBENT PADS AND TUBES AROUND SPILL AREA. CONSIGNEE ARRIVED FROM CALUMET SHORTLY THEREAFTER WITH BAGS OF "FLOOR DRY". HE AND OUR DRIVER SPREAD THE FLOOR DRY ON THE SPILL AREA. THE CONSIGNEE THEN ARRANGED FOR A FRONT END LOADED TO DIG UP CONTAMINATED SOIL AT THE EDGE OF THE STATION PAVING. HE THEN CALLED IN HIS REMEDIATION CONSULTANT.
column169: THE DRIVER HAS WORKED FOR US OVER 2 YEARS AND HA NOT HAD A SPILL BEFORE THIS. HE HAS DELIVERED TO THIS DOLLAR BAY MI STATION OVER 40 TIMES. HE WAS GIVEN A STERN VERBAL REPRIMAND FOLLOWED BY A WRITTEN LETTER OF CONSTRUCTIVE CRITICISM, A COPY OF WHICH WAS PLACED IN HIS PERSONNEL FILE. WE EMPHASIZED TO THE DRIVER THAT WHILE UNLOADING HE MUST ALWAYS BE WITHIN FIVE FEET OF THE SHUT OFF VALVES AND THAT HE MUST HAVE THE ENTIRE UNLOADING HOSE IN HIS SIGHT.  THE DRIVER REALIZED THE SPILL WAS ENTIRELY HIS FAULT AND HE ACCEPTS FULL RESPONSIBILITY FOR IT.

column168: DRIVER DID A WALK AROUND INSPECTION AND NOTICED LIQUID COMING OUT OF THE REAR OF THE TRAILER @ 1630.  TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH MATERIAL CONTAINING WHITE PHOSPHORUS UNDER WATER.  DRIVER CALLED AND NOTIFIED DISPATCH.  DISPATCH TOLD DRIVER TO CALL THE EMERGENCY CONTACT # ON THE MANIFEST.  DISPATCH ASKED DRIVER SEVERAL QUESTIONS TO CONFIRM VALIDITY OF A LEAK.  DRIVER STATED THAT WATER LEAKING WAS NO CLEAR BUT HAD RESIDUE IN IT THAT LOOKED LIKE COFFEE GROUNDS.  DISPATCH PULLED UP A PRIOR MANIFEST FOR THE SAME MATERIAL AND WITH THE INFORMATION GIVEN DECIDED THAT THE TRAILER SHOULD NOT BE MOVED AND THAT A HAZMAT TEAM NEEDED TO BE CALLED.  DRIVER WAS NOTIFIED THAT HAZMAT TEAM WAS BEING CALLED OUT AND TO TAKE PICTURES OF THE LEAK ETC.  DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO DO EVERYTHING POSSIBLE TO ISOLATE THE TRAILER AND TO KEEP THE PUBLIC AWAY.  HAZMAT TEAM WAS LOCATED AND CALLED OUT @ 1745.  HAZMAT TEAM CALLED MANAGER AT ABOUT 1945 STATED THAT BASED ON THE INFORMATION AND SEVERITY OF THE POSSIBLE OUTCOME THAT WE NEEDED TO CALL OUT THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE STATE TROOPERS.  MANAGER TOLD THEM TO DO SO.  APPROXIMATELY ONE HALF OF THE TRUCK STOP WAS EVACUATED AND CLOSED.  HAZMAT CREW ENTERED TRAILER AND FOUND NO LEAK AT ABOUT 2115.  THEY TESTED THE PH OF THE WATER ON THE FLOOR AND NOTED IT TO BE 5 OR ABOUT THE PH OF WATER.  MANAGER INSTRUCTED THEM TO PUT FLOOR DRY DOWN ON EXISITING LIQUID SO THAT WE WOULD KNOW IF A LEAK BEGAN.  DRIVERS WERE INSTRUCTED TO GO ON TO DESTINATION AND TAKE PICTURES AT THE UNLOADING SITE @ 2215.
column169: THE FOLLOWING CORRECTIVE/PREVENTATIVE ACTIONS ARE BEING TAKEN:  INCIDENT HAS BEEN ENTERED INTO OUR "CORRECTIVE ACTION PROCESS."  THE INCIDENT WILL BE ANALYZED ALONG WITH ALL ITEMS LEADING UP TO THE INCIDENT AND THE RESPONSE AND PROCEDURES FOLLOWED AFTER THE INCIDENT.  INCIDENT WILL BE DISCUSSED IN SAFETY MEETING.  SHIPPING SOP (STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE) WILL BE REVIEWED AND UPDATED IF NECESSARY.

column168: DRIVER ENTERED THE INCORRECT GAS STATION.  DRIVER TOOK A STICK READING OF TANK, BUT DID NOT VERIFY THE ULLAGE OF THE TANK.  ONCE THE ULLAGE WAS EXCEEDED, THE TANK IS OVERFILL PROTECTION FAILED TO STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT.  PRODUCT CONTINUED UP THE FILL PIPE CAUSING PRESSURE ON THE LOOSELY CONNECTED VAPOR HOSE.  VAPOR HOSE POPPED OFF CAUSING GAS TO EXIT TANK THROUGH VAPOR PORT ON COAXIAL DOWN SPOUT.  THE RELEASE HAPPENED @ APPROXIMATELY 9 PM CST & THE STORE WAS CLEANED UP AND OPERATIONAL @ 11 PM CST.  CITY OF MINNEAPOLIS FIRE APPEARED ON THE SCENE @ 8:20 PM CST.  CITY OF MINNEAPOLIS FIRE CHIEF ORDERED THE CITY STREET SWEEPER TO CLEAN UP THE STREET & CURB THAT WAS CONTAMINATED.  THE CITY OF MINNEAPOLIS IS RESPONSIBLE FOR THE DISPOSAL OF THE MATERIAL WEST CONTROL ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALLED BY KANE & SWEPT THE LOT W/ A SWEEPER ATTACHMENT ON A BOBCAT.  THE STREET WAS SWEPT AS WELL.  THE SEWER DRAIN WAS NOT IMPACTED.  THE ABSORBENT WAS REMOVED FROM THE SITE AND DISPOSED OF ACCORDING TO MN POLLUTION CONTROL AGENCY STATUTES BRINGING THE INCIDENT TO A CLOSE.  CLOSURE WAS GRANTED BY THE MN PCA ON THIS INCIDENT
column169: THE OVERFILL PROTECTION FLAPPER ON THE TANK DID NOT STOP PRODUCT FROM CONTINUING TO FLOW INTO THE TANK.  NO ALARM SOUNDED THAT COULD HAVE WARNED THE DRIVER ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE BUILDING.  THE VAPOR HOSE SHOULD HAVE HAD A SECURE FIT ON THE PORT OF THE COAXIAL DOWN SPOUT.  THE PRODUCT WOULD THEN HAVE TRAVELED INTO THE VAPOR RAIL ON LINES ON THE TRAILER.  VERIFYING ULLAGE OF THE TANK BEFORE STARTING THE UNLOAD PROCESS COULD HAVE PREVENTED THIS OVERFILL.

column168: THE PACKAGE WAS HANDLED ACCORDING TO THE DECISION TREE AND FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET.  A PORTION OF THE PACKAGE WAS PUT INTO THE DMP SYSTEM THE REMAINING CONTENTS WAS SHIPPED BACK.

ACFX 87665, LOAD TURPENTINE, WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN HAMLET, NC.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND A BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE LEAK.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR THE SOURCE OF THE RELEASE.  THE CONTRACTOR DISCOVERED THAT THE CAR WAS NOT LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE BUT PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM THE INTERNAL HEATER COIL OUTLET.  THE HEATER COIL OUTLET CAP WAS NOT APPLIED AND A SECONDARY BALL VALVE ON THE OUTLET WAS IN THE OPEN POSITION.  THE CONTRACTOR CLOSED THE BALL VALVE AND INSTALLED THE OUTLET CAP WRENCH TIGHT.  THE RELEASE STOPPED.  THE SHIPPER, SMURFIT-STONE CONTAINER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AND WAS ADVISED OF THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE.  THEY WERE ALSO ADVISED THAT THE LADING WOULD HAVE TO BE TRANSLOADED.  SMURFIT ADVISED THAT THE CAR BELONGS TO THE CONSIGNEE, MILLENNIUM SPECIALTY CHEMICAL.  MILLENNIUM WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AND THEY PROVIDED A RESIDUE TANK CAR, UTLX 70769, TO TRANSLOAD THE LADING INTO.
PLEASE REFER TO ATTACHMENT A FOR A DETAILED DESCRIPTION OF THE INCIDENT AND PICTURES OF THE INCIDENT AND SPILL CLEAN-UP.

THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER WAS CALLED TO RESPOND TO A SPILL.  HE WENT TO SPILL LOCATION AND SECURED THE AREA.  THE PACKAGE WAS ON ITS SIDE ON TOP OF ANOTHER BOX AND WAS LEAKING A LIQUID.  ON TOP OF THE BOX WERE 5 PART SHIPPING PAPERS AND ON THE SIDE OF THE BOX THERE WAS A CORROSIVE LABEL.  THE RESPONDER USING THE DECISION TREE WAS DIRECTED TO THE CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET.  THE RESPONDER READ ALL THE HAZARDS AND DONNED THE APPROPRIATE PPE.  THE RESPONDER THEN READ THE RESPONSE ACTION STEPS AND PROCEEDED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  FIRST HE CHECKED PH OF LIQUID IT WAS A 1 ON THE SCALE INDICATING IT WAS A STRONG ACID.  THE RESPONDER USED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILLED LIQUID AND FOLLOWED THE ACTION STEPS TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  AFTER ALL RESIDUES WERE CLEANED UP THE LEAKING PACKAGE, ALL SPILLED MATERIAL, AND ALL PACKAGES DAMANGED BY THE SPILL WERE MOVED TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY, 10:00 PM, SUNDAY OCTOBER 23, 2005, YARD CREW YPMO33 WAS SHIFTING INBOUND TRAIN CSXT'S "C-770".  TANK CAR UTLX 130517 (LOAD, HYDROCHLORIC ACID SOLUTION, 8, UN1789, PG II, RQ), LOCATED AT THE 19TH CAR IN THE INBOUND TRAIN, WAS INCLUDED IN THE FIRST 38 CARS THAT WERE TAKEN FROM THIS TRAIN BY THE LOCAL CR CREW TO BE SIWTCHED TO VARYING TRACKS IN THE YARD.  AFTER COMPLETION OF SHIFTING THE FIRST 38 CARS, CREW WENT DOWN TRACK TO COUPLE TO REMAINDER OF INBOUND TRAIN AND NOTICED "PUFFING" FROM THE TOP OF THE UTLX 130517 TANK CAR.  YARDMASTER NOTIFIED CR RISK MANAGEMENT A. RICHTER.  WHILE ENROUTE, MR. RICHTER ALSO CONTACTED REACT ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES FOR ASSISTANCE.  UPON ARRIVAL AT APPROXIMATELY 11:30PM, YARDMASTER ADVISED REACT REPRESENTATIVE G. BUNKER WAS ON SITE OF THE CAR AND FOUND A BLOWN 165 P.S.I. FRANGIBLE DISC (MANUFACTURED BY ZOOK) IN THE NON-RECLOSING PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE (SAFETY VENT).  DISC WAS REPLACED IN KIND, AND CAR SECURED.  CAR WAS LATER MOVED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT TO THE YARD'S SHOP TRACK, WHERE IT WAS PROTECTED AND CLEANED/DECONTAMINATED OF THE SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT RESIDUE ON EITHER SIDE OF THE CAR (CLEANING ACCOMPLISHED MONDAY, OCTOBER 24TH.)  CAR OKAYED TO ORIGINAL DESTINATION.  ADDITIONALLY NOTED AT TIME OF INSPECTION BY CR AND REACT; NOTED THE INSPECTION PLUG FOR THE SAFETY VENT CLOSURE FLANGE WAS MISSING (NOTED A CABLE WITH BROKEN END, INDICATING IT WAS PRESENT AT ONE TIME), CONTRARY TO SECTION 179.15 (F)(3) OF DOT TITLE 49 CFR.  ALSO NOTED TWO OF FOUR AIR LINE CLOSURE FLANGE SECUREMENT NUTS WERE "SHORT" (NOT FULLY ENGAGED BY THE STUDS DUE TO THE LENGTH OF THE STUDS; I.E. "SHORT BOLTS.)"

R KRUSHEWSKY, LEAD TRAINMASTER, AT APPROXIMATELY 10:00AM, ADVISING CONDUCTOR OF PR-1 CREW NOTED FROSTING ON ONE SIDE OF THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING ON TANK CAR UTLX 804705, LOAD, PROPYLENE, 2.1, UN 1075, LOCATED IN BAYWAY YARD ON TRACK #6, ELIZABETH, NJ.  MR. KRUSHEWSKY ADVISED HE HAD CONTACTED THE CONSIGNEE, CONOCO PHILLIPS (YARD IS SERVING YARD FOR CUSTOMER) FOR ASSISTANCE.  CUSTOMER ADVISED THEY WOULD NOT RESPOND.  REACT CONTACTED FOR ASSISTANCE.  SHIPPER SEAL INTACT ON PROTECTIVE HOUSING PIN (SEAL # BP-WBU 971403) AND REMOVED AT TIME OF EXAMINATION.  FURTHER INSPECTION BY REACT AND CR NOTED THE "B" END LIQUID VALVE WAS NOT COMPLETELY CLOSED; AND THE CLOSURE PLUG FOR SAID VALVE WAS MERELY CONNECTED TO THE VALVE BY NO MORE THAN 2 THREAD; ALLOWING LIQUID TO ESCAPE.  UPON OPENING THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING, SAID VALVE WAS ALMOST COMPLETELY FROZEN OVER WITH ICE FROM THE PRODUCT.  VALVE OPERATING HANDWHEEL WAS TURNED APPROXIMATELY 1/8 TURN, CLOSING THE VALVE.  OPERATING HANDWHEEL WAS THEN REMOVED.  AFTER ICE WAS REMOVED FROM THE HOUSING, THE CLOSURE PLUG FOR THE LIQUID VALVE WAS MADE TOOL TIGHT. A SLIGHT TURN COULD ALSO BE ACCOMPLISHED ON THE VALVE STEM'S PACKING NUT.  AS INFORMATION; THE MIDLAND MAGNETIC GAUGING DEVICE MEASURING ROD WAS MARKED AS: "AW-908-DWG.  #502679-40, S.G.=0.522" AND WAS MEASURING 23 3/4" OUTAGE.  INTERNAL PRESSURE AT TIME OF INSPECTION WAS "110 P.S.I."  ADDITIONAL EXCEPTIONS NOTED: VAPOR VALVE CLOSURE PLUG NOT EVEN HAND TIGHT; AND THE SAMPLE VALVE CLOSURE PLUG WAS NOT TOTALLY ENGAGING THE VALVE'S ORIFICE.  ALL FITTINGS AND CLOSURES WERE MADE SECURE.  PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER CLOSED, SECUREMENT PIN REAPPLIED, AND SECURED WITH REACT SEAL "REACT 000239."  CAR DEEMED SECURE FOR DELIVERY TO ORIGINAL DESTINATION AT APPROXIMATELY 1:30PM.

column168: OCTOBER 18, 2005.  AT APPROXIMATELY 06:50PM, CONDUCTOR OF CR YARD CREW YPCA27 (FC27) SENSED AN AMMONIA ODOR SEEMINGLY ORIGINATING FROM TANK CAR PLMX 2509 (RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, 2.2, UN 1005, PQ, INHALATION HAZARD), WHILE LOCATED ON TRACK 17-SUPPORT.  VALVES/FITTINGS BUBBLE-TESTED BY A. RICHTER, CR RISK MANAGEMENT, NOTING SLIGHT VAPOR RELEASE ORIGINATING FROM UNDERNEATH THE 300 PSI PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE (PRD) MOUNTING FLANGE.  DUE TO THE EXTREME CLOSE PROXIMITY OF OTHER VALVES, ALL ATTEMPTS TO TIGHTEN THE FOUR MOUNTING FLANGE NUTS ON THE PRD WERE UNSUCCESSFUL.  INTERNAL PRESSURE GAUGED AT 92 PSI AT TIME OF INITIAL INSPECTION.  STENCILING, ALONG WITH FURTHER CONVERSATIONS WITH U.S. STEEL-CLAIRTON WORKS, REVEALED PRD WAS REPLACED ON SEPTEMBER, 2005, BY (AS STENCILED) "MRH."  CAR WAS MOVED TO THE "ICE HOUSE" TRACK FOR ISOLATION AND ACCESSIBILITY.  ON WEDNESDAY, 10/19/05, REACT ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES DEPRESSURIZED THE VAPOR PRESSURE (INCLUDING 272 GALLONS OF PRODUCT) INTO A 4,000 GALLON-CAPACITY TANK TRUCK, WITH FURTHER VAPOR SCRUBBED INTO A 55-GALLON STAINLESS STEEL DRUM.  NITROGEN PAD INTRODUCED INTO CAR.  UPON COMPLETION, NO AMMONIA PRESSURE DETECTED.  CAR LESSEE, CONTINENTAL NITROGEN AND RESOURCES, ROSEMOUNT, MN, IS REQUESTING FRA MOVEMENT AUTHORITY FOR CAR TO BE RETURNED TO REPAUNO PRODUCTS, GIBBSTOWN, NJ, FOR CLEANING/PURGING AND INSPECTION OF PRD.

column168: MANAGER COOPER OBSERVED TRANSLOADING SERVICES REMOVING FREIGHT FROM CONTAINER CSXU 932853.  DEVELOPED THIS CONTAINER HAD ARRIVED THROUGHT THE GATE AND FOUND TO BE OVER WEIGHT WHEN THE RAMP ATTEMPTED TO LOAD IT TO A RAIL CAR.  SEVERAL HAZARDOUS COMMODITIES WERE OBSERVED INSIDE THE CONTAINER, AND THE CONTAINER WAS NOT PLACARDED.  BILLING SHOWED THE MOVE AS A GENERAL FREIGHT SERVICE MOVE.  TWO 300 GALLON IBC'S CONTAINING SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION; ONE PALLET OF 4 EACH 55 GALLON DRUMS CONTAINING FORMALDEHYDE SOLUTION; AND, TWO PALLETS OF BAGGED SULFAMIC ACID, WERE IDENTIFIED INSIDE THE CONTAINER WITHOUT PROPER SHIPPING PAPERS.  CSX WAS CONTACTED AND REQUESTED THEY CONTACT THEIR SHIPPER FOR CORRECTED HAZARDOUS DOCUMENTS.  ONCE THE PROPER PAPERWORK WAS IN PLACE, AND THE RAIL WAYBILL WAS CORRECTED TO CORRECTLY SHOW THE HAZARDOUS CONTENTS, THE CONTAINER WAS PLACARDED AND RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.

column168: AT 1845 HRS ON 10/28/05 A CSX YARD CREW AT MONTGOMERY, AL REPORTED A SWEET ODOR AND NOTICED SOME WETNESS ON THE SIDE OF RAIL CAR UTLX 203197.  THEY ALERTED THE CSX TRAINMASTER WHO ACTIVATED THE TRANSPORTATION EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN (TERP).  THE TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED AND A CSX EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, SOUTHERN WASTE SERVICES (SWS), WAS CALLED TO INSPECT AND MITIGATE THE LEAK.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE INCIDENT RHOUGH CHEMTREC REPORT #10282005081.  SWS FOUND THE LIQUID LINE PLUG LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT, ALLOWING APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT TO LEAK FROM THE TANK CAR.  THE LIQUID LINE DOES NOT HAVE A VALVE, THE PLUG WAS TIGHTENED AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  UTLX 203197 WAS STAGED FOR 2 HOURS AND THEN RELEASED FOR DISPOSITION.

ASSOCIATED PETROLEUM CARRIERS WAS MAKING A DELIVERY TO THE JOHNS ISLAND AIRPORT NEAR JOHNS ISLAND, SC.  THE DRIVER FOR ASSOCIATED PETROLEUM CARRIERS WAS USING THE PTO PUMP ON THE ASSOCIATED PETROLEUM CARRIERS' TRACTOR, BECAUSE THE PUMP AT THE JOHNS ISLAND AIRPORT WAS NOT WORKING.  WHEN THE DRIVER STARTED PUMPING, FOR UNKNOWN REASONS, THE DUST CAP ON THE T-BAR PUMP LINE CAME OFF RESULTING IN THE SPILL OF 50 GALLONS OF JET FUEL.  THE SC DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENTAL CONTROL WAS NOTIFIED AND AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR WAS HIRED TO REMEDIATE THE SPILL SITE TO THE STATE OF SOUTH CAROLINA'S CLEAN-UP STANDARDS

column168: A BNSF SWITCH CREW IN RAILYARD REPORTED ACFX 71313 DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET AREA.  A BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE BOTTOM OUTLET TO CATCH DRIPS.  THE BNSF MECHANICAL/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDER REPORTED FINDING A TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE (TOBOV) PARTIALLY OPEN WITH THE TOBOV OPERATING ROD LOOSE.  RESPONDER CLOSED THE TOBOV AND TOOL TIGHTENED THE OPERATING ROD PACKING GLAND NUT 1 1/2 TURNS.  THE PACKING MATERIAL AROUND THE OPERATING ROD LOOKED SUFFICIENT.  AFTER THE TOBOV WAS SECURED, THE PRODUCT DRIP FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP (BOC) CEASED.  RESPONDER THEN CHECKED THE BOC, FINDING IT LOOSE ON ITS THREADS (LESS THAN HAND TIGHT).  THE BOC GASKET WAS CHECKED AND FOUND TO BE DETERIORATED (DRIED AND SHRIVELED) AND FELL OUT OF THE BOC READILY.  THE BOC GASKET WAS REPLACED AND THE BOC WAS TOOL TIGHTENED.  ALL SECUREMENT WAS COMPLETED BY 2240 HRS. CST, 10/31/05.  ALL SPILLAGE EVAPORATED.

column168: INBOUND BNSF TRAIN INSPECTION IN RAILYARD REVEALED PRODUCT ODOR EMANATING FROM GATX 92721.  BNSF MECHANICAL/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDER DETECTED RESIDUE PRODUCT ODOR FROM THE 280.5 PSIG MIDLAND SAFETY RELIEF VALVE (SRV) OR PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE.  GATX 92721 WAS ISOLATED IN THE RAILYARD.  THE BNSF RESPONDER REPLACED THE SRV O-RINGS AND AFTERWARDS A SLIGHT PRODUCT ODOR WAS STILL DETECTABLE.  ALSO OBSERVED WAS A GASEOUS SEEPAGE THAT BUBBLED UP THROUGH THE WATER THAT WAS USED TO SCRUB VAPOR.  ON 10/16/05 CONTRACT RESPONDERS DEPRESSURIZED GATX 92721 AND BEGAN TO SPARGE RESIDUE PRODUCT VAPOR INTO A WATER FILLED VACUUM TRUCK.  THIS PROCESS WAS STOPPED AFTER A FROST LINE FROM AUTO REFRIGERATION WAS OBSERVED APPROXIMATELY 2 1/2 FEET ABOVE THE TANK BOTTOM ON THE UNINSULATED TANK SHELL OF GATX 92721.  ON 10/17/05, AN AMMONIA TANKER TRUCK WAS USED TO RECEIVE RESIDUE PRODUCT FROM GATX 92721.  ON 10/18/05 VAPOR SPARGING WAS RESUMED AND CONTINUED THROUGH 10/19/05.  ON 10/20/05, THE SRV WAS REPLACED IN KIND BY 0930 HRS. CDT WHILE GATX 92721 WAS UNDER A VACUUM.  NO FURTHER PRODUCT ODOR WAS DETECTED AFTER THE SRV WAS REPLACED.  THE CAUSE OF THE INITIAL SRV RELEASE IS UNKNOWN.  THE REPLACED SRV WILL BE FORWARDED TO GATX FOR FAILURE ANALYSIS.

column168: AFTER LOADING THE LOADER CLOSED THE DOME LID AND WASHED DOWN THE SPILL BOX, THEN THE DRIVER SECURED THE DOME LID LUGS.  BECAUSE A STRIPPED LUG TIGHTENED AS EXPECTED THE DRIVER DID NOT NOTICE THAT IT WAS NOT HOLDING DOWN THE DOME LID.  AFTER MOVING THE TRAILER FROM THE LOADING POINT TO THE SCALES TO CHECK OUT THE DRIVER DID NOT NOTICE THAT IT WAS NOT HOLDING DOWN THE DOME LID.  AFTER MOVING THE TRAILER FROM THE LOADING POINT TO THE SCALES TO CHECK OUT THE DRIVER DID HIS WALK AROUND CHECK.  SINCE HE EXPECTED TO SEE WATER DRIPPING FROM THE SPILL BOX DRAIN TUBS HE DID NOT RELEASE THAT HE HAD A LEAK.  ANOTHER MCKENZIE DRIVER NOTICED SOMETHING LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER AND CONTACTED OUR CNC AT 0530.  THE DRIVER WAS CONTACTED BY CELL PHONE AND STOPPED AT EXIT #116 ON I-40 IN TN.  THE TERMINAL MANAGER FOLLOWED THE ROUTE OF THE LEAKING TRAILER CHECKING SEVERAL POSSIBLE SPILL LOCATIONS AND FOUND NO EVIDENCE OF AN ACID SPILL.  THE STRIPPED LUG WAS REPLACED SOLVING THE PROBLEM.
column169: AN EXTRA STEP WILL BE ADDED TO THE DRIVERS WALK AROUND CHECK REQUIRING HIM TO CLIMB THE LADDER AND VISUALLY CHECK THE SPILL BOX AFTER MOVING FROM THE LOADING POINT BUT BEFORE DEPARTING THE PLANT.

column168: ON OCTOBER 18 2005 AT 1800 HOURS A PASSING TRAIN REPORTED THAT TANK CAR DUPX 29136, ON TRAIN Q67618 SITTING ON THE MAIN LINE WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR.  HAZARDOUS MATERIAL MANAGER ED COOK WAS NOTIFIED AT 1848 AND HEPACO INC WAS CONTACTED BY CSXT TO GO OUT AND INSPECT THE RAIL CAR.  UPON ARRIVAL AND INSPECTION OF THE CAR IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE PRODUCT METHANOL WAS LEAKING FROM UNDER THE VAPOR VALVE WHERE IT BOLTS TO THE PRESSURE PLATE ON THE CAR.  THREE BOLTS AT THE BASE OF THE VAPOR LINE WHERE TIGHTENED A 1/4 TURN EACH, AND THE PRESSURE WAS RELIEVED FROM THE CAR BY OPENING THE VAPOR VALVE.  THE LEAK STOPPED AND THE TRAIN PROCEEDED ON.  THE PRODUCT THAT LEAKED FROM THE CAR WAS CLEANED WITH ABSORBANT PADS, AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY BY HEPACO INC.

column168: DURING OVER-THE-ROAD OPERATIONS, THE DRIVER EXPERIENCED A TIRE FAILURE.  AS A RESULT, A TOTE CONTAINING ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL RELEASING 5 GALLONS TO THE INTERIOR OF THE TRAILER.  ON OCTOBER 13, 2005, AT APPROXIMATELY 7:00 PM CDT, KLLM TRANSPORT SERVICES RETAINED CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES (CES) TO MANAGE THE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN UP ON THEIR BEHALF.  BASED ON THE INFORMATION PROVIDED, THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER DISPATCHED A CREW FROM TAS ENVIRONMENTAL TO ASSESS THE SITE AND PERFORM THE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS.  THE CREW FROM TAS ARRIVED ON-SITE AND ASSESSED THE SCOPE OF THE RELEASE.  UPON ARRIVAL IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK HAD BEEN CAUSED BY INSUFFICIENT HEAD-SPACE IN A TOTE WHICH CAUSED THE CAP TO POP OFF.  THE CREW BEGAN CORRECTIVE ACTIONS BY DEPLOYING ABSORBENT MATERIALS TO THE FREESTANDING LIQUID AND THE SURROUNDING TOTES.  THE CAP ON THE LEAKING TOTE WAS TIGHTENED AND ALL THE TOTES WERE REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER.  THE TRAILER FLOOR AND TOTES WERE CLEANED.  THE CREW THEN RE-LOADED THE TRAILER AND DISPOSED OF THE SPENT ABSORBENTS IN ONE (1) 55-GALLON DRUM.  THE CREW PREPARED THE WASTE FOR DISPOSAL AND DEMOBILIZED.

column168: On October 19, 2005, diesel fuel was spilled/leaked from a 4,000-gallon tanker truck trailer as the result of traffic accident. The accident occurred when the driver swerved to avoid an object in the road. The tanker trailer rolled onto its side and ruptured, releasing approximately 2,800 gallons of diesel onto Mamalahoa Highway. The spilled diesel ran approximately 400 feet northwest along the southeastern shoulder of the highway to a culvert outlet. The spilled diesel then ran approximately 190 feet northeast within an unnamed stream (flowing with water from the culvert) with two waterfalls and small ponds at the base of each waterfall, and ended up in a marsh approximately 400 feet from the coastline. The spilled diesel impacted asphalt and soil along the highway, as well as water in the stream and marsh. Field observations on October 19 through 21, 2005 indicated that the spilled diesel did not reach the Pacific Ocean or otherwise impact it. Hawaii Petroleum, Inc. (HP1) orally reported the release to the National Response Center (NRC); Hawaii County Police and Fire Departments (HP and ITFD); Hawaii Department of Transportation (HDOT); Hawaii Department of Health, Hazard Evaluation &   Emergency Response Office (DOll-BEER). HP! submitted a Hawaii Hazardous Substance Written Follow-up Not Wcation to the DOH-HEER. Based on the release notification, the DOH-HEER has assigned Case No.20051019-0924 to the spi LI. Spill Response

column168: Driver pulled into the store at approx. 4:30am.  Headed west, the fuel islands are to the left of the truck. The driver continues on past the fuel island, with the trailer approx. halfway past the fuel island.  The driver attempts turn to the left, when he does the trailer comes in contact with a safety pole that is approx. 6 feet tall. The pole punctures a hole in the trailer about mid point of the barrel of the trailer, which leaks gasoline out onto the ground.  The driver feels the truck and trailer slow because of the poles, and a smaller pole has also come in contact with the fitting box on the trailer, destroying it.     Failure to the trailer is a puncture in the #3 compartment of trailer; hole is 8 inches in length and 2 inches wide. Puncture was created from a 6-foot pole at fuel island, spilling 1800 gallons of gasoline.     Haz-Mat Inc. was called to clean up spill and location.

column168: A TRACTOR TRAILER OWNED BY BONDED OIL COMPANY WAS INVOLVED IN AN ACCIDENT ON 10/21/2005.  THE ACCIDENT TOOK PLACE IN THE MORNING ACROSS THE STREET FROM OUR HEADQUARTERS.  THE VEHICLE TURNED OVER AND WAS UPSIDE DOWN.  DRIVER WAS NOT INJURED FROM THE ACCIDENT AND WAS ABLE TO GET OF THE VEHICLE.  DRIVER CALLED HQ AND A RESPONSE TEAM FROM BONDED WAS DISPATCHED.  BONDED'S RESPONSE TEAM WAS THERE WITHIN 3 MINUTES OF THE ACCIDENT.  THE STORM DRAINS WERE COVERED SO NO PRODUCT COULD ENTER AND THE HEATING THAT WAS LEAKING FROM THE TANKER WAS CONTAINED.  THE TRAILER LEAKED IN A FEW SMALL SPOTS WHERE THE TANK WAS WELDED TOGETHER.  A ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED BY THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES AND TOGETHER BOTH RESPONSE TEAMS CLEANED THE RELEASE.
column169: BONDED OIL COMPANY HAS ALWAYS INCLUDED DRIVER SAFETY INTO OUR TRAINING.  WE USE THIS INCIDENT AS TEACHING TOOL TO HELP DRIVERS UNDERSTAND THE IMPORTANT OF BEING FOCUSED AND BEING SAFE.  I THINK DRIVER SAFETY COURSES THAT ARE REQUIRED BY INSURANCE COMPANIES IS AN EXCELLENT TOOL.  OUR INSURANCE COMPANY HAS ALWAYS VEEN HANDS ON WITH DRIVER SAFETY.  WE WOULD NORMALLY DO A DRIVER SAFETY CLASS ONCE A QUARTER.  AFTER THE INCIDENT WE PERFORM DRIVER SAFETY EVERY MONTH.

column168: ON TUESDAY, OCT 25TH @1:35PM, MAXYFIELD CLIENT RON GIRRES WAS APPLYING NH3 ON HIS FARM. AFTER APPLYING ABOUT 20 ACRES HE TURNED TO THE LEFT AND THE COUPLER LOOSENED FROM THE TANK VALVE. THIS CAUSED THE RELEASE OF NH3 AND PROMPTED RON TO CALL FOR HELP. AT 1:40 WE HAD PEOPLE AT THE SITE, ASSESSED THE SITUATION AND CALLED THE LOCAL F.D. THEY SUITED UP WITH PROPER PPE, MISTED THE TANK AND VAPOR CLOUD, AND 2 FIRE FIGHTERS SIMPLY WALKED UP AND CLOSED THE VALVE. THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND PERS WERE ALSO CALLED. THE DNR ALSO WERE CALLED AND UPDATED AS TO EXTENT OF THE RELEASE AND WHAT WAS DONE. (SEE COMPLETE REPORT AND PHOTOS ATTACHED).                                                                   J.W.
column169: CONTINUE TO EDUCATE FARMERS ON THE IMPORTANCE OF PROPERLY CONNECTING A TANK TO THE TOOLBAR. AS POINTED OUT IN MY REPORT, EMPLOYEES RECEIVE NH3 TRAINING PRIOR TO THE NH3 SEASON. (TWICE PER YEAR). FARMERS REALLY HAVE NO FORMAL TRAINING AND LEARN BY EXPERIENCE AND WHAT WE TELL THEM WHILE HOOKING THEM UP FOR THE FIRST TIME. A FORMAL TRAINING CLASS WOULD BE BENEFICIAL FOR THE FARMERS, AND WE WOULD BE THE FIRST TO TRY SOMETHING LIKE THIS. MIGHT JUST WORK.                                        J.W.

column168: -OCTOBER 17, 2005   MR. VAZQUEZ WAS TRAVELING THROUGH A CONSTRUCTION ZONE PROCEDDING NORTH BOUD ON IH-610 EAST UNAWARE OF THE ELEVATION CHANGE FROM THE MAIN FREEWAY TO THE FEEDER ROAD, AND THE SHARPNESS OF THE CURVE HE WAS ABOUT TO ENCOUNTER. HE BEGAN EXECUTION OF A LANE SHIFT, FROM THE MAIN FREEWAY TO THE FEEDER ROAD. AS HE PROCEEDED THROUGH THE LANE SHIFT AN AUTOMOBILE SWERVED FROM THE LEFT LANE ACROSS THE RIGHT LANE TO TAKE THE MARKET STREET EXIT. IN ORDER TO AVOID CONTACT WITH THE AUTOMOBILE MR. VAZQUEZ WAS FORCED TO TURN HIS STEERING WHEEL HARD LEFT. BEING IN A SEVERE LANE SHIFT TO THE RIGHT AND ON UNEVEN ASPHALT THE MOMENTUM CAUSED THE TRUCK TO ROLL ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE.     -EMERGENCY RESPONSE   KIM HUGGINS RECEIVED A CALL FROM MILSTEAD ENVIRONMENTAL NOTIFYING HER THAT ONE OF BDS TRUCKS WAS TURNED OVER AT 610 NORTH AND MARKET STREET. AFTER VERIFYING THAT IT WAS INDEED A BDS TRUCK, BUT NOT KNOWING THE EXTENT OF THE DAMAGES, KIM HUGGINS INSTRUCTED JAMES TO DISPATCH SOMEONE TO THE SCENE TO ASSESS THE SITUATION AND TOLD HIM THAT SHE WOULD BE RIGHT BEHIND THEM.  MRS. HUGGINS VERIFIED THE CONTAINER CONTENTS TO BE 18 (330 GALLON) TOTES OF TETRABUTYLTIN, DIBUTYLTIN DICHLORIDE UN2922 AND LEFT FOR THE SCENE    -APPROXIMATELY 0900 HOURS CST   KIM HUGGINS ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AND WAS MET BY JAMES WITH MILSTEAD, REPRESENTATIVES FROM THE HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT, TCEQ, AND TX DOT. THE HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD CONFIRMED THAT THERE WAS A PRODUCT LEAK FROM THE CONTAINER, A SMALL AMOUNT OF WHICH HAD GONE DOWN A STORM WATER DRAINAGE SYSTEM INLET LOCATED APPROXIMATELY 60 FEET SOUTH OF THE POSITION OF WHERE THE TRAILER HAD COME TO REST DURING THE ACCIDENT. AT THAT POINT MRS. HUGGINS WAS INFORMED THAT TXDOT HAD PLACED AN EARTHEN DYKE AROUND THE INLET TO PROTECT AGAINST ADDITIONAL PRODUCT REACHING THE DRAINAGE SYSTEM.  VIA CELLULAR PHONE MRS. HUGGINS WAS INFORMED THAT BDS WOULD NOT BE USING MILSTEAD AS THE RESPONSE TEAM AS MATT MARTELLI OF XL SPECIALTY CLAIMS HAD ARRAIGNED FOR USES TO RESPOND.    -APPROXIMATELY 1045 HOURS CST,   MR. CORY ANDERSON, HAZMAT MANAGER WITH USES ARRIVED ONSITE AND MET WITH KIM HUGGINS OF BDS AND MR. MATT ALLEN WITH THE TCEQ AS WELL AS REPRESENTATIVES FROM TXDOT AND CITY OF HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT.   AN ONSITE MEETING WAS HELD TO BRING USES UP TO DATE ON THE SITUATION AND TO DISCUSS HOW THE PRODUCT REMAINING IN THE TOTES WOULD BE HANDLED DURING THE MITIGATION EFFORTS.   IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE DAMAGED TOTE(S) WERE LOCATED AT THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER, THEREFORE THE REMAINING 17 TOTES HAD TO BE MOVED OUT OF THE CONTAINER TO ASSESS THE DAMAGE AND DETERMING HOW TO HANDLE THE CLEAN UP. THERE WAS CONCERN THAT THE OTHER 17 TOTES MIGHT ALSO BE DAMAGED AND THAT MOVING THEM WITH CONTENTS IN TACT MIGHT CAUSE ADDITIONAL SPILLS AND/OR PROBLEMS AND THAT THE CONTENTS WOULD NEED TO BE TRANS-LOADED IN ORDER TO MOVE THE TOTES.  IT WAS DECIDED THAT A 10 BBL (CAPABLE OF HOLDING 70, 55 GALLON BARRELS OF LIQUID) STAINLESS STEEL VACUUM TRUCK WOULD BE UTI

THE RELEASE WAS DISCOVERED ON OCTOBER 19, 2005 AT APPROXIMATELY 2:50 P.M.  ON A RETURN TRIP FROM CANTON, OHIO, EMERALD'S TRUCK DRIVER WAS TRAVELING ON I-77 NORTH TO I-76 EAST TO THE ROUTE 43 EXIT.  HE DID NOT NOTICE ANY PROBLEMS WHILE TURNING ONTO ROUTE 43.  THE TRUCK DRIVER THEN TRAVELED DOWN TO ROUTE 261 AND MADE A RIGHT TURN ONTO ROUTE 261.  SHORTLY AFTER TURNING ONTO ROUTE 261, A DRIVER OF A CAR STOPPED THE EMERALD TRUCK AT THE INTERSECTION OF ROUTE 261 AND SUMMIT STREET AND INFORMED EMERALD'S TRUCK DRIVER THAT THE TRUCK WAS LEAKING.  EMERALD'S TRUCK DRIVER PULLED OVER TO THE SIDE OF ROUTE 261, JUST PAST THAT SUMMIT STREET INTERSECTION, AND SAW THAT THERE WAS A LEAK COMING FROM THE BACK OF THE TRUCK.  THE MATERIAL RELEASED WAS WASTE SULFURIC AND HYDROCHLORIC ACID.  THE RELEASE OCCURRED FROM A 55-GALLON DRUM ON A TRANSPORT TRAILER.  THE CAUSE WAS A 55-GALLON OPEN LID POLY DRUM THAT FAILED.  AFTER NOTIFYING A DISPATCHER AT EMERALD, THE TRUCK DRIVER SOUGHT TO TRAVEL BACK TO EMERALD'S FACILITY WHICH WAS MINUTES AWAY.  THE TRUCK DRIVER CONTINUED TRAVELING DOWN ROUTE 261 AND MADE A RIGHT TURN ONTO ROUTE 59 (HE DID NOT WANT TO MAKE A LEFT TURN BECAUSE IT WOULD TAKE HIM INTO DOWNTOWN KENT.)  EMERALD'S TRUCK DRIVER THEN TURNED AROUND IN THE WAL-MART PARKING LOT ON ROUTE 59 AND PROCEEDED TOWARDS THE EMERALD FACILITY IN KENT, OHIO BY MAKING A LEFT TURN ONTO ROUTE 261, TRAVELING TO FRANKLIN TO MATINEL DRIVE TO ST. CLAIR.  AFTER THE TRANSPORT TRAILER ARRIVED AT EMERALD, EMERALD'S EMPLOYEES ACCESSED THE SITUATION.  THE TRUCK DRIVER AND OTHER EMPLOYEES WIPED DOWN THE TRAILER FLOOR USING ABSORBENT MATERIALS AND LIME.  AT APPROXIMATELY THE SAME TIME, SCOTT HERSHBERGER (EMERALD EMPLOYEE) LEFT EMERALD TO ACCESS WHETHER ANY OF MATERIAL WAS ON THE ROADWAYS.  SHORTLY AFTER LEAVING EMERALD, MR. HERSHBERGER CAME ACROSS REPRESENTATIVES OF THE CITY OF KENT FIRE DEPARTMENT, WHO WERE RESPONDING TO AN ODOR ISSUE.  MR. HERSHBERGER INFORMED THE KENT FIRE DEPARTMENT OF THE SITUATION AND DISCUSSED POSSIBLE RESPONSE ACTIVITIES.  THE KENT FIRE DEPARTMENT CONTACTED OHIO EPA AND THE PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION OF OHIO ("PUCO").  REPRESENTATIVES OF THE OHIO EPA AND PUCO ARRIVED ON SCENE.  EMERALD, IN CONJUNCTION WITH ITS EMERGENCY CONTRACTOR, WASHED DOWN SECTIONS OF ROUTES 43, 59, AND 261 WITH CITY OF KENT WATER.  IN ADDITION, EMERALD PLACED LIME (A NEUTRALIZING AGENT) ON A SPILL AREA LOCATED ON THE ROUTE 43 BRIDGE OVER I-76.  THE CITY KENT CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT, THE OHIO EPA AND OTHER LOCAL AND STATE REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE INVOLVED IN OVERSEEING THE CLEAN UP ON THE ROADWAY.  EMERALD COMPLETED THE CLEAN UP OF THE STREETS TO THE SATISFACTION OF OHIO EPA AND THE CITY OF KENT.  EMERALD VERBALLY NOTIFIED OHIO EPA'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE SECTION, THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER ("NRC") AND LOCAL AUTHORITIES.
column169: WITH RESPECTS TO PROGRAMS, EMERALD HAS NUMEROUS PLANS, AS WELL AS SUBSTANCIAL TRAINING PARAMETERS, THAT ADDRESS SITUATIONS SUCH AS THE INCIDENT OF OCTOBER 19.  AFTER THE INCIDENT, EMERALD'S PANS AND TRAINING WERE REVIEWED BY THE IN-HOUSE SAFETY OFFICER.  HIS RECOMMENDATIONS WERE LIMITED TO: A) IMPROVING COMMUNICATIONS; B) ACQUIRING ADDITIONAL EQUIPMENT TO SECURE DRUMS FOR DRUM TRANSPORT; C) EMPHASIZING THE USE OF EQUIPMENT TO CONTAIN SPILLS IN THE EVENT OF AN ACCIDENT; AND D) RE-TRAINING DRIVERS RELATIVE TO SECURING LOADS.

column168: WHILE DOING AN EQUIPMENT INSPECTION AT LOCK HAVEN YARD, LOCK HAVEN, PA., FRA MP&E INSPECTOR PAVUSCKO DISCOVERED GATX 15256 LEAKING BUTYL ACRYLATE AROUND THE BELLY VALVE OF THE CAR.  THE RATE OF THE LEAK SEEMED TO BE 1 DROP PER 20 SECONDS.  MR. PAVUSCKO NOTIFIED A LOCAL NBER TRAIN CREW WORKING IN THE YARD OF THE LEAK AND THEY NOTIFIED P.E. LUCAS, NBER GENERAL MANAGER.  IT IS BELIEVED THAT MR. PAVUSCKO ALSO CALLED MR. BOB BUNDY, FRA HAZ MAT INSPECTOR WHO NOTIFIED THE MAIN RAILROAD OFFICE.  ALL OF THIS TOOK PLACE IN THE TIME FRAME FROM 1201 TO 1220.  AT 1230 CLINTON COUNTY 911 WAS NOTIFIED AND THEIR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE TEAM AND LOCAL FIRE COMPANY WERE DISPATCHED.  (REPORT 4279) AT 1234 THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS NOTIFIED (REPORT 776860), 1245 CHEMTREC (INCIDENT # 10202005-070) WAS NOTIFIED AND BASF CORP (SHIPPER) MR. DOUG PHIEL WAS NOTIFIED AT 1309.  MR. LUCAS ARRIVED ON SCENE AT 1326 AND TALKED WITH MR. PAVUSCKO CONFIRMING HE HAD NOTIFIED THE TRAIN CREW OF THE LEAK.  AT 1330 MR. LUCAS AND MR. PHIEL HAD A CONFERENCE CALL IN WHICH MR. LUCAS DESCRIBED THE NATURE AND LOCATION OF THE LEAK.  LOCAL HAZ-MAT RESPONSE TEAM WAS ON SITE BUT NOTIFIED THE PRINCIPALS THAT THEY DO NOT WORK ON TANK CARS.  DURING THIS TIME A 5 GALLON BUCKET HAD BEEN PLACED UNDER THE VALVE TO CONTAIN THE LEAK.  1340 MR PHIEL INDICATED HE WOULD CALL HIS OWN RESPONSE TEAM.  1344 MR. PONTIUS, VICE-PRESIDENT OPERATIONS ARRIVED WITH SPILL CONTAINMENT BARREL AND PIGS WHICH WERE PUT IN PLACE.  1433 - PA. DEP AGENT ARRIVED ON SCENE TO ACCESS ANY ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE.  HMHTTC RESPONSE TEAM ORDERED BY BASF CORP. ARRIVED ON SCENE AND DETERMINED THE BELL NUT ON THE BELLY VALVE WAS THE LOCATION OF THE LEAK.  THE RESPONSE TEAM USED A 36 IN PIPE WRENCH TO TIGHTEN THE BELL NUT AND STOP THE LEAK.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONSIGNEE FOR UNLOADING.

column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, TYPE A PACKAGE, SPECIAL FORM NON FISSILE OR FISSILE-EXCEPTED
column168: THE DAMAGE TO THE FIBERBOARD BOX HAPPENED DURING THE MVOEMENT IN THE BAGGAGE CART TO THE OUTBOUND AREA.  THE TOP OF THE FIBERBOARD WAS OPENED DURING THE TRANSIT OF THIS PACKAGE CAUSING ONE OF THE INNER PIGS TO FALL OUT OF THE COMPROMISED PACKAGE, AS WELL AS THE BAGGAGE CART DURING THE TRANSIT.  THIS DAMAGED PACKAGE WAS NOT DISCOVERED UNTIL THE BAGGAGE CART ARRIVED AT THE OUTBOUND SORTING AREA.  AFTER SEARCHES BY THE HUB SPILL RESPONSE TEAM, THE LOCAL SAFETY OFFICE, AND THE DANGEROUS GOODS ADMINISTRATION SPECIALISTS, THE MISSING PIG WAS NEVER LOCATED.  IT IS SUSPECTED THIS INNER PIG WAS SWEPT UP BY THE CLEAN-UP CREWS ON SATURDAY AM.  THS STATE OF TN, RADIOLOGICAL HEALTH, HEALTH PHYSICIST GRIGSBY STEVENS VISTED THE SITE ON 11-1-2005.  KEN HOLMAN WITH THE MEM/FAA CAME BY THE SORT FACILITY TO INVESTIGATE ON 11-1-2005, AND VIEWED THE DAMAGED PACKAGE.  ON 11-14-2005, SR. HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ENFORCEMENT SPECIALIST THOMAS LYNCH, FROM THE SW REGION, AND KAREN PLESSAS SR. TRAFFIC ENFORCEMENT SPECIALIST OF THE SPECIAL INVESTIGATIONS OFFICE IN WASHINGTON DC ARRIVED TO INVESTIGATE.  STATE OF TN RADIOLOGICAL HEALTH ALSO RETURNED AT THIS TIME.
column169: THE PERSONNEL INVOLVED IN THIS INCIDENT HAVE BEEN REMINDED OF CORRECT STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURES AT FEDEX.  BETTER PACKAGING MAY HAVE PREVENTED THIS INCIDENT.

column168: AT 1340HRS ON 10-26-05, FRANK LERCH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THAT ROBERT HANRAHAN, BEAUMONT DIRECTOR OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS REPORTED TANK CAR UTLX 950787 WAS LEAKING.  CAR HAD BEEN SET OUT AND IOSLATED IN THE COWBOY TRACK.  MGR. LERCH RESPONDED AND REQUESTED THAT RMCC MAKE SHIPPER NOTIFICATION VIA CHEMTREC.  ON ARRIVAL, LERCH NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AND RUNNING DOWN THE SIDES OF THE CAR AND EVAPORATING INTO THE ATMOSPHERE.  INSPECTION OF THE CAR REVEALED THE B END LIQUID PLUG VALVE TO BE OPEN 1/8 TURN, AND THE LIQUID VALVE PLUG TO BE IN POSITION, HAND TIGHT.  AFTER LERCH CLOSED THE VALVE, AND TIGHTENED THE PLUG, THE LEAK AWAS STOOPED.  FURTHER INSPECTION REVELALED THE VAPOR PLUG VALVE AS OPEN 1/8 TURN, WITH THE PLUG IN POSITION, HAND TIGHT AND THE SAMPLE LINE NEEDLE VALVE PLUG TO BE IN POSITION HAND TIGHT.  AFTER TIGHTENING OF ADDITIONAL FITTINGS, THE CAR WAS SECURED FROM FURTHER LEAKAGE, AND RELEASED TO CONTINUE ONTO DESTINATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS, OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.  THERE WAS NO CLEAN UP OR REMEDIATION REQUIRED AS PRODUCT EVAPORATED UPON EXPOSURE TO THE ATMOSPHERE.  ORIGINAL SEAL PROTECTING PROTECTIVE HOUSING: #1089139; REPLACED WITH UPRR CTS: #0008797.

column168: ICTF SECURITY, REPORTED LEAKING CONTAINER NOSU 445427, PLACARDED CORROSIVE, CURRENTLY LOCATED AT YELLOW 537.  DEAN COOPER, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED AND RESPONDED.  AT 03:27PM, MANAGER COOPER ADVISED THE CONTAINER WOULD BE MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK CONTAINMENT AREA FOR INSPECTION.  MR. COOPER FURTHER ADVISED NONE OF THE LEAKING PRODUCT HAD HIT THE GROUND, HOWEVER, ONE OF THE DRUMS HAD LEAKED IN TRANSIT, AND THE PRODUCT TRAIL WAS NOW DRIED.  THE LADING WAS DOUBLE STACKED DRUMS THAT WERE NOT PROPERLY SECURED OR LOADED.  SINGLE 2X4'S HAD BEEN PLACED ACROSS THE REAR OF THE DRUMS, AND FITTED INTO THE CORRUGATED SIDE WALLS OF THE CONTAINER.  THE DRUMS WERE ON PALLETS WITH NO BI-LEVEL SEPARATION.  JOE POINTEK, SHIPPER PLANT SAFETY ENGINEER, CONTACTED MANAGER COOPER TO ARRANGE FOR REMOVAL OF THE DRUMS TO LOCATE THE LEAKER.  DURING THE REMOVAL OF THE 2X4'S, IT WAS NOTED THAT ONE OF THE UPRIGHT 2X4'S HAD A NAIL THAT WENT THROUGH THE SIDE WALL OF ONE OF THE POLY DRUMS ON THE SECOND TIER.  THE LADING AND CONTAINER WERE CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE, AND THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM FOR SECUREMENT.  THE LADING WAS PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER, PROPERLY SECURED FOR OVER THE ROAD DELIVERY, AND RELEASED TO THE CONSIGNEE.

column168: DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, REPORTED TANKCAR GATX 73749 LEAKED PRODUCT BETWEEN THE MANWAY COVER PLATE AND NOZZLE WHILE IN THE LOS NIETOS, SANTA FE SPRINGS, CA.  INSPECTION OF THE TANK CAR DEVELOPED THE MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE LOOSE, APPROXIMATELY 3/4 TURN.  MANAGER COOPER TORQUED THE BOLTS, BUT PRODUCT WAS STILL LEAKING FROM THE MANWAY WHILE THE TANK CAR MOVED.  THE TANK CAR WAS SET OUT AND ISOLATED IN YARD TRACK #8.  MANAGER COOPER STATED ONE TO TWO GALLONS OF PRODUCT SPILLED DOWN THE SIDE OF THE TANKCAR.  CHEMTREC NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO REQUEST SHIPPER NOTIFICATION.  ALL STATE AND FEDERAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  ON 10/10/05, 12:05AM, ROY HILL, SOLVAY INTEROX, INC., REQUESTED AND WAS TRANSFERRED TO MANAGER COOPER.  DISCUSSION OF A TEMPORARY MANWAY GASKET MADE OF GOR-TEX MATERIAL BEING COMPATABLE WITH THE PRODUCT WAS INCONCLUSIVE, AND IT WAS DECIDED THE PROPER PTFE GASKET WOULD BE SHIPPED THE FOLLOWING MORNING.  ONCE THE MANWAY GASKET WAS REPLACED, THE CAR WAS ONCE AGAIN MOVED TO CHECK FOR PROPER SECUREMENT.  PRODUCT AGAIN LEAKED PAST THE MANWAY AND THE NOZZLE.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HAVE THE PRODUCT OFF LOADED AND TRANSPORTED TO THE CONSIGNEE BY TRUCK.  ONCE EMPTY, THE TANK CAR WILL RETURN TO THE ORIGIN SHIPPER TO BE CLEANED AND THEN SENT TO A SHOP FOR REPAIRS.
