column168: AT 1605HRS FRANK LERCH, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED TANK CAR GATX 89113 WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING.  CAR WAS LOCATED ON THE MAINLINE AT MILE POST 248.78, LAFAYETTE SUBDIVISION, BEAUMONT, TX.  MGR LERCH RESPONDED TO THE LOCATION, AND REQUESTED THE RMCC TO MAKE SHIPPER NOTIFICATION VIA CHEMTREC.  WHILE ENROUTE, MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY BRIAN SOSSAMAN, EMERGENCY RESPONSE COORDINATOR FOR LYONDELL/EQUISTAR CHEMICAL.  MR. SOSSAMAN INDICATED THAT A RESPONSE TEAM WOULD BE ORGANIZED, AND ON STANBY.  ON ARRIVAL, MGR LERCH MET WITH BEAUMONT FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL WHO WERE PREPARING TO APPROACH THE CAR AND DETERMINE THE SOURCE OF THE RELEASE.  AFTER INITIAL GROUND INSPECTION OF THE CAR, IT WAS DETERMINED THE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP UNDER THE COMBINATION HOUSING AT A RATE OF 1 QUART EVERY 15 MINUTES.  WITH THE ASSISTANCE OF FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL, MGR LERCH INSPECTED THE CAR.  THE 2 INCH LIQUID BALL VALVE WAS FOUND 1/3 OPEN, AND THE LIQUID VALVE PLUG WAS IN POSITION, AND LOOSE 1 % TURNS.  AFTER CLOSING OF THE LIQUID VALVE, AND TIGHTENING OF THE LIQUID VALVE PLUG, THE LEAK STOPPED AND THE CAR WAS SECURED FROM FURTHER RELEASE.  MGR LERCH REQUESTED SHIPPER PERSONNEL RESPOND TO CLEAN AND FURTHER INSPECT THE CAR.  ON THEIR ARRIVAL, THEY CLEANED AND INSPECTED THE CAR, AND APPLIED A BIO REMEDIAL LIQUID TO KILL THE ODOR AND REMEDIATE THE RELEASED PRODUCT.  MGR. LERCH REQUESTED ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR.  UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES RESPOND AND APPLY ADDITIONAL REMEDIATION BUGS, AND SPRAY THE AREA WITH ADDITIONAL DEODORIZER.  AFTER REMEDIATION WAS COMPELTED, THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE ONTO DESTINATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS, WATERWAYS IMPACTED, OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.  ORIGINAL SEAL PROTECTING COMBINATION HOUSING: CVO-111439; REPLACED BY SHIPPER WITH CVO-119543,44,55.

column168: BRIAN KLINE, MANAGER OF ROAD OPERATIONS, REPORTED AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT OF SULFURIC ACID WAS LEAKING FROM GATX 50948 AT RIO RICO, ARIZONA.  THE LEAK WAS OBSERVED DURING A MECHANICAL INSPECTION.  THE LEAK WAS CONTAINED TO THE TANKCAR.  MR. DENNIS JOHNSON, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, ADVISED THAT THE MANWAY COVER WAS NOT WRENCHED TIGHT AND THE MANWAY GASKET WAS PINCHED.  THE MANWAY COVER LID SWING BOLT HAD TOO MUCH PLAY AND WOULD NOT ALLOW THE LID TO BE SECURED TIGHT.  MR. JOHNSON FURTHER ADVISED REPAIRS HAD BEEN MADE BY REPLACING THE SWING BOLT, APPLING A NEW GASKET AND PROPERLY SECURING THE CAR FOR MOVEMENT.
column169: REVIEW PROPER LOADING AND SECUREMENT INSTRUCTION WITH SHIPPER.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Vapor Valve
column168: TIM BESSERMAN, ASSISTANT TRAIN MASTER, REPORTED A SMALL VAPOR CLOUD EMITTING FROM THE MANWAY COVER ON TANKCAR TIMX 33412 WHICH HAD BEEN PLACED IN AN ISOLATED AREA OF THE ALTON SOUTHERN RAILYARD IN EAST SAINT LOUIS, IL.  DOUG BRUECK, TRAIN MASTER, WAS ON SCENE AND ADVISED AN EMPLOYEE IN THE AREA WAS REPORTED TO HAVE BECOME BRIEFLY ILL DUE TO THE VAPOR THAT WAS EMITTED BUT REFUSED ANY MEDICAL ATTENTION.  JOHN MILLER, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  AT 04:06 AM, MILLER ADVISED THE VAPOR VALVE WAS PARTIALLY OPEN AND THE VALVE PLUG WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED.  THE VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THE VALVE PLUG WAS SECURED.  NO PRODUCT RELEASED ONTO THE TANKCAR OR THE GROUND.  THE TANKCAR WAS RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION.

column162: OPS MGR FLEET MTCE CAN + USA
column168: PER YOUR REQUEST, ON OCTOBER 5, 22005 WE TRAVELED TO COUNTY ROAD 52, IN HARPERSVILLE, NY TO OBSERVE THE TRANSFER OF 39000 POUNDS OF SODIUM HYDROGEN SULFIDE, WHICH WAS IN METAL CANISTERS, IN LIQUID FORM, SENSITIVE TO MOISTURE AND HAD BEEN MOVED TO THIS RURAL LOCATION FOR SAFETY AND SECURITY REASONS.  WE ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT 930 AM EST AND MET WITH HAL PIGER, THE ENVIRONMENTAL EXPERT WHO WAS SUPERVISING THE TRANSFER.  OUT OF THE 9 CANISTERS IN QUESTION, ONLY FOUR WERE FOUND TO BE DEFECTIVE. HOWEVER, BEFORE THIS HAD BEEN DETERMINED, MR. PIGER HAD TO BE PREPARED FOR A WORST-CASE SCENARIO AND THEREFORE A NEW CLIMAN TRAILER WAS ORDERED TO ARRIVE AT THE SCENE, SO THAT UP TO 18 CANISTERS (9 NEW, 9 OLD) COULD BE ACCOMODATED IF NECESSARY.  WE NOTE THAT FROM 930 AM TO NOON, THE UNDERSIGNEE OBSERVED MR. PIGER AND HIS CREW PREPARE THE GROUND BY REMOVING TWIGS AND OTHER NATURAL DEBRIS FROM THE GRASS, OVER WHICH  TRANSFER OPERATIONS WERE TO BE ACCOMPLISHED. WE PHOTOGRAPHED  THE ORIGINAL TRAILER FROM THE SOUTHWEST AND NORTHWEST, AS WELL AS THE TRANSFER TENT WHICH HAD BEEN ERECTED ADJACENT TO THE OLD TRAILER. THE SUBSTANCE IN QUESTION IS FLAMMABLE UPON CONTACT WITH MOISTURE, AND THERE HAD BEEN HEAVY RAINS THE DAY BEFORE, AND SOME MILD SPRINKLING THROUGHOUT THE EARLY MORNING OF OCTOBER 5.  WE WERE ALSO ADVISED THAT UNTIL THE MORNING MIST AND FOG LIFTED, OPERATIONS WOULD BE SUSPENDED. THE MIST INDEED CLUNG TO THE GROUND UNTIL ALMOST NOON.   AT NOON, THE UNDERSIGNED STOPPED HIS BILLABLE TIME FOR THIS FILE, AND TRAVELED INTO BINGHAMTON, NY FOR WORK ON AN UNRELATED CASE, ARRIVING BACK AT 145 PM, IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE REPLACEMENT TRAILER, MENTIONED ABOVE HAD ARRIVED. BY 4 PM, 2 OF THE FOUR DEFECTIVE CANISTERS HAD BEEN SUCCESSFULLY TRANSFERRED.  THE FOURTH AND FINAL CANISTER WAS TRANSFERRED BETWEEN 530 AND 600 PM EST, AT WHICH TIME THE UNDERSIGNED LEFT THE SCENE.
column169: DUE TO THE EVENTS LEADING UP TO THIS INCIDENT THE DRIVER WAS FIRED.

column62: Human Error; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: I first heard that our driver, Harbey Munoz, was missing from my dispatcher at about 11 a.m. My dispatcher had made numerous attempts to contact him, after viewing a television report indicating there was a tank truck fire occurring on Bruckner Blvd. He called me and told me that the truck looked like ours and we could not get in touch with our driver.  I immediately called our fleet manager, Albert Cirino, who was closer to the scene of the accident. He called me and told me that it was Harbey. Our insurance company was notified and they immediately sent Miller Environmental Group to the accident to start the clean up. I, myself, headed to the Bronx where I was met by detectives from the 41” Precinct, Kevin Stockert from Highway #1, Special Accident Investigations Unit, The NY/FBI Terrorist Task Force, officials from the Police, Fire and DOT Units, Con Ed, Keyspan, Amtrack, Nynex and the Hazmat Units. I was told that Mr. Mark Berger, from the NYSDOT, had called my fleet manager and told him to expect a call from a Ms. Melissa Townsend from the U.S. DOT. She called to schedule an operation audit, after which time, a satisfactory rating to operate was given.  By the time I arrived at the scene, the fire was out. There was sand and foam spread out all over the area. I learned from Detective Stocker, from Highway 1, that he suspected the driver had been speeding. The truck had come around a sharp turn traveling at 47 MPH. I learned that the sand had been pushed out into the street by Casa Building Material, located about 75 feet from the truck fire, when fuel started to leak from the truck. This alone was able to contain a large part of the oil from traveling further, preventing a bad situation from becoming even worse.  I had first suspected that a truck, coming out of the Casa Building Material Company yard, had somehow cut off Harbey. I hired a private investigator to look into this. (I have enclosed his report). I believe now, that this accident was indeed caused by driver error.  I have since hired Mr. Anthony Natale to coordinate monthly meetings with the drivers, to implement safety procedures, while operating their trucks. Attendance for all drivers is mandatory. These meetings have noticeably improved our daily work habits.  I assumed that because Ms. Melissa Townsend of DOT performed the audit, and indeed knew of the accident, that the department would have been notified by her. Having never dealt with an accident of this nature, or with a job related fatality, we were not sure of the proper procedure with forms. While we do not anticipate any accident to this degree to occur, should anything as unfortunate as this accident ever happen to us again, we will be fully prepared as far as procedures are concerned. I am enclosing a copy of Ms. Townsend’s satisfactory rating for our company.  Here is a list of all contacts, which were involved.  Highway Patrol Unit #1: Kevin Stoeckert (718)822-5815  41” Detective Squad: Medina & Swanson (718) 542

At 2050 on 10-26-05 Wheeling & Lake Erie Railway (WLE) 251-26 crew called into dispatch that their train was in emergency. The head end was at approximately MPQ68 of our Cleveland sub division. The crew began to walk their train and found the  36th-43rd cars derailed and tank cars were on their side derailed. Dispatch intructed train crew to return to the head end and wait for WLE responding supervision. At 21:30 Jim Hill, Division Superintendent on site, notified myself:, Jeff Clapper, and WLL dispatch that UTLX 202293 was leaking. Dispatch called Chemtrec and the shipper, Jeff Clapper contacted local fire emergency personnel and the Ohio EPA. UTLX 202293 was leaking from a damaged bottom outlet valve. The leak was stopped at 0300, 10-27-05 through a combined effort of Eagle Environmental, WLE contractor, WLE personnel ar.d local first responders by the use of a magnet clamping patch device. Spilled, pooled product (acetone) was recovered and disposed of. The product in UTLX 202293 was transloaded to tank car GATX 25895, which was provided by WLE. This car was an empty acetone car in Sunoco’s service, the shipper. The transload was completed at 0400 on 10-28-05. Car was rerailed at approximately 1000 on 10-28-05.    The derailment was caused by wide gauge. The 36 car in the train dropped into the rail when the train went into emergency rail broke under the train. A piece of broken rail struck the bottom outlet valve of the UTLX 202293 tank car which was the 39th car in the train. When the valve was struck by the broken rail it knocked the bottom flange of the valve body off causing the bottom outlet valve to leak.
